Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

At first We'll be focused on whether or not the patients showed up for their appointments as we examine a little over 100k medical appointments in Brazil for this dataset.¶

Numerous variables will need to be taken into account, including demographics (such as age and gender) and chronic diseases or conditions (such as alcoholism, diabetes, hypertension, and disability). Finding out whether or not these elements are directly related to patients turning up for or skipping out on their appointments is the aim.

Question(s) for Analysis¶

what is the relation between (show-up) and all columns??
Is there is any relationship between three variables of interest?????

++++++NOTE++++++¶

"neighbourhood" where the hospital is located is referred to as If a patient is engaged in Bolsa Familia, a welfare programme in Brazil, it is indicated by the term "Scholarship."

Making a function to facilitate the work of graphs and avoid code duplication

In [45]:
def myplot(df,grpvar):
    fig,(ax1,ax2)=plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(14,6))
#plot1**************
    df.groupby(grpvar)['no-show'].value_counts().unstack().plot.bar(alpha=.8, ax=ax1, rot=0);
    ax1.set_title(f'Comparing between {grpvar} and show up: Counts'.title(), weight='bold')
    ax1.set_xlabel(grpvar)
    ax1.set_ylabel('Number of Patients');
 #plot2*************             
    df.groupby(grpvar)['no_show_numeric'].mean().plot(kind='bar', ax=ax2, rot=0);
    ax2.set_title(f'Comparing between {grpvar} and show up: Proportions'.title(), weight='bold')
    ax2.set_xlabel(grpvar)
    ax2.set_ylabel('oportion No Shows');
 #plot3*************                
    df.groupby(grpvar)['no-show'].value_counts().unstack(grpvar).plot(subplots=True, kind='pie', figsize=(14,6),explode=[0,0.1], autopct='%1.2f%%' );
    plt.suptitle(f'comparing between {grpvar} and show up'.title(), weight='bold')

In [ ]:

Looking at our analyzes, we found that:¶

1) The data and the histogram demonstrate that approximately 25% of both sexes were no shows (did not show up for their appointment), whereas approximately 75% of both sexes did. Furthermore, there were more females than males in both the cases of shows and no shows.Therefore, it cannot be said that gender and performance are clearly correlated.
2) Around 10% of people enrolled in the welfare programme and around the same number of those not enrolled in welfare failed to show up for their appointments, respectively. Since there is little correlation between shows and no shows, participation in the welfare programme does not seem to be a significant issue.
3) Because both hypertensive and non-hypertensive patients have almost the same ratio of shows to no shows, hypertension seems to be a negligible impact.
4) Diabetes doesn't seem to be a significant issue because both diabetic and non-diabetic patients have around the same ratio of shows to no shows.
5) Alcoholism appears to have a negligible impact because both alcoholics and non-alcoholics had almost the same ratio of shows to no shows.
6) Being disabled does not appear to be clearly correlated with attending or missing the appointment, making it a negligible issue.
7) The number of attendees at their appointment who didn't receive an SMS was significantly higher than the number of attendees who did! Approximately 56 percent of those who received an SMS and 70 percent of those who did not showed up for their appointment.
8) The age group of 10 and under had the highest turnout, followed by that of 35 to 70. It is apparent that people attend appointments less frequently as they age and get older. 9) Jardim Camburi, one of the neighbourhoods, seems to host the most performances.
It seems that whether or not the patient shows up for their appointment depends a lot on the neighbourhood.

Conclusions:¶

1) Neighborhood: Appears to have a direct correlation with patients attending their appointments.
2) Age: Those under 10 and people in the 35–70 age range appeared to be more prevalent than people in other age groups.
3) SMS received: It was surprised to learn that more people turned up without receiving an SMS reminder, even though it may not be causally related.

4) We found through the questions we asked that females attend more than men and at the same time they are more absent.
5) The higher the age, the higher the non-attendance rate.
6) Those without scholarships are the most present and the most absent.
7) Those with high blood pressure are less present. People with diabetes are also the least present, the same is true for drunkards and people with disabilities who have received SMS messages.
8) As when making a relationship between gender and the rest of the columns, we found that the percentage of non-attendance is greater for both sexes, but women are more in non-attendance.
9) While women are the most affected by high blood pressure, and the same is true in the case of diabetes, drunks, disabilities and those receiving SMS messages, we find that women have the majority.
10) We also find that there is an influence in all aspects, where the columns affect each other
11) Limitations: We were unable to discover a relationship between the number of shows and the other variables, including gender, diabetes, hypertension, disability, welfare status, and drunkenness.
